22/russia.crash/|title=Russian jet crash kills all 170 on board|publisher=CNN|date=2006-08-23|accessdate=2009-10-10|first=Matthew|last=Chance}}</ref>\n* [[August 24]] &ndash; The [[International Astronomical Union]] [[2006 definition of planet|defines]] '[[planet]]' at its 26th General Assembly, demoting [[Pluto]] to the status of [[dwarf planet]] more than 70 years after its discovery.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn9824-pluto-gets-the-boot-as-the-planet-count-drops.html|title=Pluto gets the boot as the planet count drops|work=[[New Scientist]]|accessdate=2009-10-10|date=2006-08-24|first=Stephen|last=Battersby}}</ref>\n\n===September===\n\n* [[September 19]] &ndash; The [[Royal Thai Army]] overthrows the government of [[Prime Minister of Thailand|Prime Minister]] [[Thaksin Shinawatra]] in a ''[[2006 Thai coup d'\u00e9tat|coup d'\u00e9tat]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cctv.com/english/20060920/100287.shtml|title=Coup d\u00b4etat launched in Thailand|agency=[[Xinhua News Agency]]|accessdate=2009-10-10|date=2006-09-20|first=Sun|last=Luying}}</ref>\n* [[September 29]] &ndash; [[Gol Transportes A\u00e9reos Flight 1907]] collides with a business jet over the [[Amazon rainforest]], killing all 154 on board the former.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-19078146_ITM|title=Passports of Legacy jet pilots seized pending investigation in Brazil crash.|publisher=Europe Intelligence Wire|accessdate=2009-10-10|date=2006-10-04}}</ref>\n\n===October===\n* [[October 6]] &ndash; [[Fredrik Reinfeldt]] replaces [[G\u00f6ran Persson]] as [[Prime Minister of Sweden]].\n* [[October 9]] &ndash; [[North Korea]] claims to have conducted its first-ever [[2006 North Korean nuclear test|nuclear test]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2006/oct/09/northkorea|title=North Korea claims first nuclear test|work=The Guardian|date=2006-10-09|accessdate=2009-10-11 | location=London}}</ref>\n* [[October 13]] &ndash; South Korean [[Ban Ki-moon]] is elected as the new Secretary-General of the United Nations, succeeding [[Kofi Annan]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/5401856.stm|title=Profile: Ban Ki-moon|publisher=BBC|date=2006-10-13|accessdate=2009-10-11}}</ref>\n* [[October 17]] &ndash; The [[United States]] population reaches 300 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.wikinews.org/wiki/US_population_reaches_300_million|title=US population reaches 300 million|website=en.wikinews.org/}}</ref>\n\n===November===\n* [[November 2]] &ndash; ''[[No. 5, 1948]]'' by [[Jackson Pollock]] becomes the [[List of most expensive paintings|most expensive painting]] after it is sold privately for [[List of most expensive paintings|$140 million]].<ref name=\"Artnet\">{{cite web | url= http://www.artnet.com/magazineus/news/artmarketwatch/artmarketwatch11-3-06.asp | title= Art Market Watch | date=November 3, 2006 | accessdate=2006-11-08 | publisher= Artnet}}</ref>\n* [[November 5]] &ndash; Former [[President of Iraq]] [[Saddam Hussein]] is [[Execution of Saddam Hussein|sentenced to death]] by hanging by the [[Supreme Iraqi Criminal Tribunal|Iraqi Special Tribunal]]. He is later executed by hanging for crimes against humanity on [[December 30]].<ref name=\"ap burial\">{{cite news|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/national/1107AP_Saddam.html |title=Saddam buried in village of his birth |agency=Associated Press |date=2006-12-31 |accessdate=2006-12-31 }}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>                                         \n* [[November 12]] &ndash; The breakaway state of [[South Ossetia]] holds a [[South Ossetian independence referendum, 2006|referendum]] on independence from [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/11/11/AR2006111101247.html|title=Georgia: Separatist Vote Illegitimate|agency=Associated Press|first=Maria|last=Danilova|accessdate=2009-10-12|date=2006-11-11|work=The Washington Post}}</ref>        \n* [[November 23]] &ndash; A series of [[23 November 2006 Sadr City bombings|car bombs and mortar attacks]] in [[Sadr City]], [[Baghdad]], kills at least 215 people and injure 257 other people.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/15873863|title=Iraqi militias take fiery revenge for slaughter|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=2009-10-12|date=2006-11-25}}</ref>\n\n===December===\n* [[December 5]] &ndash; The military seizes power in [[Fiji]], in a [[2006 Fijian coup d'\u00e9tat|coup d'\u00e9tat]] led by Commodore [[Frank Bainimarama]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cctv.com/english/20061205/100939.shtml|title=Fiji\u00b4s troops seize police weapons|accessdate=2009-10-12|date=2006-12-05|publisher=[[China Central Television]]|first=Du|last=Xiaodan}}</ref>\n* [[December 11]] &ndash; [[Felipe Calder\u00f3n]] sends the Mexican military to combat the drug cartels and put down the violence in the state of Michoac\u00e1n, initiating the [[Mexican Drug War]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Mexico's president pledges to continue fighting cartels|url=http://articles.cnn.com/2011-12-04/americas/world_americas_mexico-president-speech_1_drug-war-strategy-cartels-human-rights?_s=PM:AMERICAS|accessdate=January 27, 2012|newspaper=CNN|date=December 4, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120127111118/http://articles.cnn.com/2011-12-04/americas/world_americas_mexico-president-speech_1_drug-war-strategy-cartels-human-rights?_s=PM%3AAMERICAS|archivedate=January 27, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[December 24]] &ndash; [[Ethiopia]] admits its troops have [[War in Somalia (2006\u201309)|intervened in Somalia]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/6207333.stm|title=Ethiopia dismisses Somali threat|publisher=BBC|accessdate=2009-10-13|date=2006-12-24}}</ref>\n* [[December 26]] &ndash; An [[2006 Abule Egba pipeline explosion|oil pipeline explodes]] in [[Nigeria]]'s commercial capital, [[Lagos]], killing at least 200 people.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087&sid=aknYME.Q75II|title=Nigerian Pipeline Explosion Kills at Least 200 (Update1)|website=[[Bloomberg.com]]|accessdate=2009-10-13|date=2006-12-26|first=Helene|last=Fouquet}}</ref>\n* [[December 29]] \u2013 UK settles its [[Anglo-American loan]], post-WWII loan debt.\n\n==Births==\n<!-- Please do not add yourself, non-notable people, fictional characters, or people without Wikipedia articles to this list. No red links, please. -->\n* [[January 27]] &ndash; [[Kim Su-an]], South Korean actress \n* [[March 12]] &ndash; [[Lee Re]], South Korean child actress \n* [[June 23]] \n** [[Lee Chae-mi]], South Korean actress \n** [[CX Navarro]], Filipino child actor\n* [[June 25]] &ndash; [[Mckenna Grace]], American actress\n* [[July 25]] &ndash; [[Konomi Watanabe]], Japanese actress \n* [[September 6]] &ndash; [[Prince Hisahito of Akishino]], Japanese prince\n* [[October 5]] &ndash; [[Jacob Tremblay]], Canadian actor\n* [[November 16]] &ndash; [[Mason Ramsey]], American singer\n\n==Deaths==\n{{Further|:Category:2006 deaths}}\n{{BD ToC|deaths|section=2}}\n\n===January===\n{{Main|Deaths in January 2006}}\n[[File:Sudharmono Official Portrait.jpg|120px|thumb|[[Sudharmono]]]]\n[[File:Coretta Scott King.jpg|120px|thumb|[[Coretta Scott King]]]]\n* [[January 2]] &ndash; [[Lidia Wysocka]], Polish actress (b. [[1916]])\n* [[January 3]] &ndash; [[Bill Skate]], 5th Prime Minister of Papua New Guinea (b. [[1953]])\n* [[January 4]]\n** [[Irving Layton]], Romanian-Canadian poet (b. [[1912]])\n** [[Maktoum bin Rashid Al Maktoum]], Prime Minister of the United Arab Emirates (b. [[1943]])\n* [[January 6]] &ndash; [[Lou Rawls]], African-American singer, songwriter and actor (b. [[1933]])\n* [[January 7]] &ndash; [[Heinrich Harrer]], Austrian mountaineer, explorer and author (b. [[1912]])\n* [[January 9]] &ndash; [[W. Cleon Skousen]], American conservative author and professor (b. [[1913]])\n* [[January 14]] &ndash; [[Shelley Winters]], American actress (b. [[1920]])\n* [[January 15]] &ndash; [[Jaber Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah]], 13th Emir of Kuwait (b. [[1926]])\n* [[January 19]]\n** [[Anthony Franciosa]], American actor (b. [[1928]])\n** [[Wilson Pickett]], American singer (b. [[1941]])\n* [[January 21]] &ndash; [[Ibrahim Rugova]], Kosovar writer, scholar and political leader (b. [[1944]])\n* [[January 24]] &ndash; [[Chris Penn]], American actor (b. [[1965]])\n* [[January 25]] &ndash; [[Sudharmono]], 5th [[Vice President of Indonesia]] (b. [[1927]])\n* [[January 27]] &ndash; [[Johannes Rau]], 8th President of Germany (b. [[1931]])\n* [[January 29]] &ndash; [[Nam June Paik]], South Korean-born American artist (b. [[1932]])\n* [[January 30]] &ndash; [[Coretta Scott King]], American civil rights activist (b. [[1927]])\n\n===February===\n{{Main|Deaths in February 2006}}\n[[File:Betty Friedan 1960.jpg|thumb|120px|[[Betty Friedan]]]]\n[[File:Don Knotts Barney Fife 1966.JPG|thumb|120px|[[Don Knotts]]]]\n* [[February 3]] &ndash; [[Al Lewis (actor)|Al Lewis]], American actor (b. [[1923]])\n* [[February 4]] &ndash; [[Betty Friedan]], American feminist, activist, and writer (b. [[1921]])\n* [[February 8]] &ndash; [[Akira Ifukube]], Japanese classical music/film composer (b. [[1914]])\n* [[February 10]] &ndash; [[J Dilla]], American music producer (b. [[1974]])\n* [[February 12]] &ndash; [[Peter Benchley]], American writer (b. [[1940]])\n* [[February 13]]\n** [[Andreas Katsulas]], American actor (b. [[1946]])\n** [[P. F. Strawson]], English philosopher (b. [[1919]])\n* [[February 15]] &ndash; [[Sun Yun-suan]], 10th Premier of the Republic of China (b. [[1913]])\n* [[February 18]] &ndash; [[Sirr Al-Khatim Al-Khalifa]], 5th Prime Minister of Sudan (b. [[1919]])\n* [[February 21]] &ndash; [[Mirko Marjanovi\u0107]], 63rd Prime Minister of Serbia (b. [[1937]])\n* [[February 22]] &ndash; [[Said Mohamed Djohar]], 2-Time President of the Comoros (b. [[1919]])\n* [[February 23]] \u2013 [[Telmo Zarra]], Spanish f